{
  "text": "In this study we examined how mutations in different structural and regulatory genes affect the organization of V. fischeri biofilms both in vitro and in juvenile E. tasmanica. Vibrio fischeri forms biofilms in diverse habitats, including the environment and the squid host, which correspond to different ecological lifestyles. In the environment, there are multiple fluctuations of salinity and temperature that have a direct effect upon colonization and persistence [CITATION_1] , but our knowledge of the genes that are important for in vitro biofilm formation and hence host colonization is limited.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "13935947"
